<div metal:fill-slot="body">

<h3>About Markdown</h3>

<style type="text/css">
td.st-o { 
    font-family:'Courier New', Courier; 
}

td.st-r { 
    font-family:Arial, Verdana, sans-serif; 
    background-color:#cccccc;
}

</style>

<div class="bumf">
<p style="font-weight:bold;">Markdown is a lightweight markup language. 
The language takes many cues from existing conventions for marking up plain text in email.</p>
<p>See <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markdown">Wikipedia article on Markdown</a></p>
</div>



<table align="center" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
  <td width="30%"><p><strong>You enter...</strong></p></td>
  <td width="30%" class="st-r"><p><strong>You get...</strong></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="st-o">Sam said: *I* did **not** do _it_</td>
  <td class="st-r">Sam said: <em>I</em> did <strong>not</strong> do <em>it</em></td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="st-o">Send [email](mailto:info@foo.com) to<br /> [Foo.com](http://www.foo.com)</td>
  <td class="st-r">Send <a href="mailto:info@foo.com">email</a> to <a href="http://www.foo.com">Foo.com</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="st-o">Line breaks<br />don't matter.<br /><br />Only paragraph breaks<br />do.</td>
  <td class="st-r">Line breaks don't matter.<br /><br />Only paragraph breaks do.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="st-o">Inline `code` and block code:<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;while (!perl) {<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;print "Python";<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}</td>
  <td class="st-r">Inline <code>code</code> and block code:
<pre style="background-color:#eeeeee;">
 while (!perl) {
    print "Python";
 }
</pre></td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td class="st-o">- Bulleted lists can be...<br/>- Written using '-', '*' or '<code>o</code>'...<br />- Or using numbers like <code>'1.'</code>, <code>'2.'</code>, etc.</td>
  <td class="st-r"><ul>
<li>Bulleted lists can be...</li>
<li>Written using '-', <code>*</code> or <code>o</code>...</li>
<li>Or using numbers like <code>1.</code>, <code>2.</code>, etc.</li>

</ul></td>
</tr>
</table>

